: 
<taxonomicName authority="Riedel, 2020" authorityName="Riedel" authorityYear="2020" box="[1176,1397,1085,1106]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Hoplismenus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="380" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flagellator" status="spec. nov.">Hoplismenus flagellator</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1397,1084,1136]" box="[151,736,1114,1136]" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">
spec. nov. : 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[279,303,1114,1135]" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">18</emphasis>
. face, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[362,386,1114,1135]" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">19</emphasis>
. head from dorsal, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[571,595,1114,1135]" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">20</emphasis>
. basal tergites.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,757,1191,1825]" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">
striation. 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[269,286,1191,1205]" fontSize="6" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">nd</superScript>
tergite 1.3x wider than long. Gastrocoelus impressed, with strong ridges; thyridium almost transverse, c. 0.75x as wide as the interval. 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[573,590,1255,1269]" fontSize="6" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">nd</superScript>
and 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[658,672,1255,1269]" fontSize="6" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">rd</superScript>
tergites densely punctate, without median rugae. 4 
<superScript attach="left" box="[612,625,1287,1301]" fontSize="6" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">th</superScript>
tergite with fine dense punctures, following tergites with very superficial punctures. 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[351,368,1351,1365]" fontSize="6" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">nd</superScript>
to 4 
<superScript attach="left" box="[424,437,1351,1365]" fontSize="6" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">th</superScript>
sternites with median folds. Ovipositor sheath slightly extending behind metasomal apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,757,1191,1825]" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">
Color: Black. Flagellum black, central flagellomeres (c. 8-13) ± reddish ventrally, but flagellum without clear pale ring. Palps, mandible centrally and median spot on face reddish. Collare and tegula red; scutellum with dark reddish shine. Postpetiolus apically, 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[568,585,1575,1589]" fontSize="6" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">nd</superScript>
tergite entirely and lateral spots on 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[376,390,1607,1621]" fontSize="6" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">rd</superScript>
tergite red. 7 
<superScript attach="left" box="[529,542,1607,1621]" fontSize="6" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">th</superScript>
tergite with median ivory spot. Coxae and trochanters black; hind trochantellus red; mid femur except red apex and hind femur completely black. Tibiae and tarsi red; hind tibia with weak infuscation in apical 0.1. Wings slightly yellowish; pterostigma yellow-red.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,757,1191,1825]" box="[151,293,1801,1825]" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">: unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="380" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,757,1865,2081]" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,238,1865,1889]" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">Remark</emphasis>
: Due to the ventral edge of hind coxa, this new species belongs to the group E4 sensu 
<bibRefCitation author="HILPERT, H." box="[559,730,1897,1921]" pageId="15" pageNumber="380" pagination="1 - 389" refId="ref17096" refString="HILPERT, H. 1992: Zur Systematik der Gattung Ichneumon LINNAEUS, 1758 in der Westpalaearktis. - Entomofauna Supplement 6: 1 - 389." type="journal article" year="1992">HILPERT (1992)</bibRefCitation>
. It is characterized by the erect pilosity on head and mesosoma, modified form of mandible, and absence of pale flagellar ring.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,757,1865,2081]" lastBlockId="15.[794,1398,1193,1313]" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">
In the key for Siberian 
<taxonomicName authority="(RIEDEL, 2018)" baseAuthorityName="RIEDEL" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[411,703,2025,2049]" class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Ichneumon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="380" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[411,528,2025,2049]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">Ichneumon</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="RIEDEL, M." box="[543,696,2025,2049]" pageId="15" pageNumber="380" pagination="1509 - 1562" refId="ref17262" refString="RIEDEL, M. 2018: Contribution to the Siberian species of Ichneumon LINNAEUS (Hymenoptera, Ichneumonidae, Ichneumoninae). - Linzer Biologische Beitrage 50: 1509 - 1562." type="journal article" year="2018">RIEDEL, 2018</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, this new taxon runs to couplet 46 (
<taxonomicName authority="RIEDEL" authorityName="RIEDEL" box="[487,873,1194,2081]" class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Ichneumon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="380" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mandibulatus">
<emphasis box="[487,757,2057,2081]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">Ichneumon mandibulatus</emphasis>
RIEDEL
</taxonomicName>
). It differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[1053,1220,1193,1217]" class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Ichneumon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="380" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mandibulatus">
<emphasis box="[1053,1220,1193,1217]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">I. mandibulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the slenderer mandible, erect pilosity, mainly black 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1213,1227,1223,1237]" fontSize="6" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">rd</superScript>
tergite, absence of ivory spots on 5 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1006,1019,1255,1269]" fontSize="6" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">th</superScript>
and 6 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1092,1105,1255,1269]" fontSize="6" pageId="15" pageNumber="380">th</superScript>
tergites, and dark reddish scutellum.
</paragraph>
